ities and lands as conquerors or enemies, but as liberators.  Your wealth has been stripped of you by<br>
unjust men. ... The people of Baghdad shall flourish under institutions<br>
which are in consonance with their sacred laws. ... The Arab race may<br>
rise once more to greatness!&quot; -- Gen. F. S. Maude, commander of the British forces when he captured Baghdad in 1917<br>
(From Neil Baird's The News Report,Issue 684, Monday March 31 2003 -<br>
subscribe via news-report-subscribe@wiretapped.net )<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->We all know the result of that. Another century of puppet regimes favorable to the West's business interests, until Saddam took power, again promising autonomous power to the Arabs. Now, we've done it for/to them again.<br>
<br>
And no, we didn't need to conquor Canada, Mexico, Venzuela, etc to get favorable policies from their governments for oil. We aready have that, without installing a puppet regime.<br>
<br>
And no, that list of reasons for moving into Iraq wasn't all-inclusive. Don't forget the immense amounts of money made by politicians and their lobbyists and campaign-funding corporations by the military actions. Spare parts alone run several times the original contracted cost of a weapons system. Each Tomahawk cost ~$600 thousand out the factory door, but the real cost of putting it in the field with payroll, etc for all the delivery platforms was probably several million plus.<br>
Operations costs run much more than this, and that's just the immediate costs (the instant money given to the pentagon to carry out the operations). The next year's DOD budget requests will be higher than ever.<br>
<br>
Note that this money doesn't get packed into missile warheads and shot out over the battlefields; it goes to political districts. The non-military beltway bandit &quot;think tank&quot; people in favor of the war, along with the generals &amp; politicians get money from the contractors, some of them get jobs running military contract departments with the companies after they retire.<br>
<br>
Cheney's old buddies in Halliburton aren't the only beneficiaries of the war. Just the first. Just as the British left in place political interests favorable to getting the oil out at the expense of the native peoples'  interests, we won't really install any systems capable of letting the Iraqis running their own democracy.<br>
 In Japan after 1945, we created a serious competitor. We'll create a puppet for our best interests. Short-sighted, admittedly, but better in the short term for the gang of crooks running things now.<br>
<br>
